ocr.sentence: matter the king was very glad hereof, and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg-ment that I shall appoint they all answered, that they were.
ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 221 the matter the kingwas very glad hereof,and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg ment that I shaU appoint they all answered, that they were. Then were they bid to returne three days after. In that time Fryer Bacon had caused the body of their deceased father to be taken out of the ground, and brought to the court the body hee did cause to be bound to a stake, naked to the middle upwards and Hkewise prepared three bowes and shafts for the three brethren all these kept hee secretly. The third day being come, came these three brethren, to whom Fryer Bacon in the presence of the king gave the three bowes and shafts, saying, be not offended at what I have done, there is no other way but this to judge your cause See here is the body of your dead father, shoot at him, for he that cometh nearest to his heart, shad have aU the lands and goods. The two eldest prepared themselves, and shot at him, and stucke their arrowes in his breast. Then bid they the youngest to shoot but he refused it, saying, I will rather loose aU, then wound that body that I so loved living Had you ever had but halfe that love in you to him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled, than to suffer his lifelesse corps thus to be used nay, you doe not onely suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame and speaking this, he wept.

ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 295 whereat his master had great marvade then they sate downe to breakfast, which being ended they went home, and did such thinges as were there to bee done when his dame sawe that he had so soone ended his busines, she thought that he was a profitable servant, and said Httle but let him alone. In the evening Rush de maunded of his master what hee should doe the next morrow ? his master appointed him twice so much as hee did the day before, which Rush refused not, but got up earely in the morning, and went to the field, and about his worke so soone as his master was ready, he tooke his man's breakfast and came to the field, thinking to helpe Rush but he was no sooner come from his house but the Priest came to see his wife, and presently shee made ready some good meate for them to be merry withall, and whyle it was a dressing, they sate sporting together, who had beene there should have seene many loving touches. And when the goodman came to the field, he found that Rush had done aU that which he appointed, whereof he had great marvade then they sate dovroe to breakfast, and as they sate together, Rush beheld his master's shoone, and perceived that for fault of greasing they were very hard then said Rush to his master, why are not your shooes better greased ? I marvade that you can goe in them, they be so hard, have you no more at home ? Ves, said his master, I have another payre lying under a great chest at home in my chamber. Then said Rush I wdl goe home and grease them that you may put them on to-morrow and

In the evening Rush de-maunded of his master what hee should doe the next morrow ? his master appointed him twice so much as hee did the day before, which Rush refused not. but got up earely in the morning, and went to the field, and about his worke so soone as his master was ready, he tooke his man's breakfast and came to the field, thinking to helpe Rush but he was no sooner come from his house but the Priest came to see his wife, and presently shee made ready some good meate for them to be merry withall, and whyle it was a dressing, they sate sporting together, who had beene there should have seene many loving touches. And when the goodman came to the field, he found that Rush had done all that which he appointed, whereof he had great marvaile then they sate downe to breakfast, and as they sate together, Rush beheld his master's shoone, and perceived that for fault of greasing they were very hard then said Rush to his master, why are not your shooes better greased ? I marvaile that you can goe in them, they be so hard, have you no more at home ? Yes, said his master, I have another payre lying under a great chest at home in my chamber. Then said Rush I will goe home and grease them that you may put them on to-morrow and

Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. ocr.region: 247 OF FRYER BACON. told the other young man, this his father had received wrong. He answered againe, that it was faire. At last there grew such foule words betweenc them, and their bloods were so heated, that they presently stabbed one the other with their daggers, and so fell downe dead. Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came. This made him to grieve exceedingly be iudging that they had received the cause of their deaths by this glasse, tooke the glasse in his hand, aud uttered words to this effect Wretched Bacon, wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding wretched for thy art hath beene the ruine of these two gentlemen. Had I been busied in those holy things, the which mine order tyes me to, I had not had that time that made this wicked glasse wicked I weU may cad it, that is the causer of so vde an act would it were sensible, then should it feele my wrath but being as it is, He ruin it for ruining of them and with that he broke his rare and wonderftdl glasse, whose Hke the whole world had not. She went in and told him all that had passed betweene her and her son. She then beganne to make some reproofes, and desired him to put away the things that gave occasion of his griefe. He told her that the cause of his grief was his breaking of his glasse, and that he would be glad to haue it. He said also that he would be contented to haue no more of it. This made his mother to weep a great while, and then she told him, that though he had broken his glasse, yet it had not beene worth so much, but that he had broken his order. ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 269 o cette scne se passait. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melcbior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melcbior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? Hlas 1 quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Tout mdecin a sur lui sa petite pharmacie. Ils touchaient  la porte de Marguerite. Ludovic passa r-solment et enjamba les degrs sans mme jeter un nom au concierge. Mal lui en prit. On sait  quel homme il avait af-faire, c'tait un casuiste en matire d'attributions il s'lana  la poursuite de l'intrus. - Monsieurl s'cria-t-il, Monsieur! Ludovic tait dj loin. Mais le docteur y avait mis moins de zle, et ce fut sur lui que le concierge se rabattit. - O allez-vous, Monsieur? lui dit-il en lui barrant le pas-sage. Le docteur et t embarrass de le dire. Il avait suivi son ami et ignorait ehez qui ils allaient. - O je vais? dit-il avec un peu d'impatience mais vous le voyez bien. - Comment, je le vois? mais je vois que vous tombez sur mon escalier comme une bombe sans me dire seulement gare, ni me fournir un mot d'explication. Voil ce que je vois. - J'accompagne mon camarade, dit le docteur en essayant de s'ouvrir un chemin laissez-moi passer. - Votre camarade? Il est aussi peu gn que vous 1 - Voyons, finissons-en. La querelle s'chauffait, et l'austre concierge tait bien dcid  faire respecter ses consignes, dtlt-il compromettre l'intgrit de ses membres. Il avait pris la rampe  deux mains et s'arc-boutait de manire  ce qu'il ne restt point d'espace libre sur les degrs. A moins de violence, le pas-sage tait infranchissable, et le docteur n'osait pas pousser les choses si loin. Heureusement Ludovic se ravisa sans lui, l'affaire ne pouvait pas s'arranger il prit le parti de des-cendre.

ocr.sentence: La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme.
ocr.region: LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE 9 III LA FERME DE BEAUSJOUR L A feuille  la main, le sergent, debout devant l'abri du colonel, faisait la rpartition des postes. - Duruy, dit-il, tu vas monter avec tes hommes au secteur I, tu longeras un peu la route jusqu'aux boyaux B 1 et B 2, au tournant du ruisseau, ils sont perpendiculaires  la Grande Transversale, aprs quoi tu monteras tout droit jus-qu'au poste du commandant. Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!. Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  da borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. - Pour une belle nuit, c'est une beMe nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! - Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  ehaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

ocr.sentence: CE PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si. peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui ! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul mais une force imprieuse et presque indpen-dante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers ? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, .comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur Peut-tre, hlas ! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je trouv le dernier mot de ces rticences. La suite ne l'a que trop prouv j'tais dj touche, j'entrais dans cette srie de faiblesses qui m'ont perdue. C'est ici que j'ai besoin de votre pardon, Ludovic, d'un pardon absolu et gnreux. Point d'excuse possible, rien qui puisse pallier ce commen-cement de trahison. Vous aviez t pour moi le meilleur, le plus dvou et le plus fidle des amis vous n'aviez qu'une pense, mon bonheur qu'un but, notre union. Jamais, c'est une justice que je me plais  vous rendre, aucun chagrin ne m'est venu de vous si j'exprimais un dsir, vous vous em-pressiez de le satisfaire si j'avais un ennui, vous vous offriez - le partager. Vous tiez de ces loyaux compagnons qu'une femme est trop heureuse de rencontrer dans sa vie, qui l'as-sistent dans les bons et les mauvais jours et se donnent sans rserve comme sans calcul. Je voyais tout cela, je le sentais et ne mconnaissais point-vos mrites. Lui, au contraire, qu'tait-il et quel fonds pouvais-je -

prediction.region: ntrevoir dans son coeur, dans sa pense ? Je ne pouvais rien me figurer, tout m'est demeur inexpliqu. Avez-vous remarqu que, quand on ne connat rien  autrui, lorsqu'on ignore ce qui se passe dans son coeur et dans sa cervelle, on se trompe toujours ? En me fiant  mon instinct je me trompais. Vous, qui m'aimiez, qui vouliez seulement me bien, je croyais que vous aviez la mme pense que moi, j'imaginais qu'on partageait les mmes ides, qu'on avait la mme affection pour moi. Il me semble pourtant que je le devinai si bien et qu'il eut cette mme pense qu'il en devint jaloux. 258 Vous vous trompez, Ludovic, en jugeant de la passion que j'prouvais pour lui. Peut-tre vous le deviniez sans savoir le dire et vous en aviez la preuve. Il fallait que ce ft l son secret. Vous tes bien sr, c'est tout ce que vous avez  dire et vous n'avez pas voulu me demander si je l'aimais ? Mais il y a une question qu'il ne faut pas poser, c'est la dernire, je l'ai dit, c'est celle qui nous arracherait  tout notre bonheur. Vous savez, Ludovic, que j'aime et que j'aime avec passion. Je le crois, je vous l'ai dit, je l'aime et ne vois pas en lui l'homme que j'aime. Je me flatte, je me le dclare, je m'y efforce, mais je n'y arrive pas. Je le vois, je le sens, je le connais, mais je ne le crois pas. Il est impossible que je le croie et cela ne m'est pas possible, je crois, je veux croire, mais je n'y parviens pas. Je le vois, je le sens, je le connais. C'est ce que j'avais dit  cette femme. Tout est dit, je ne le verrai jamais. Il ne sera jamais pour moi ce qu'il est pour vous et vous ne serez jamais pour lui ce que vous tes pour moi. Que faire donc ? Que faire de ces sentiments ? ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. ocr.sentence: he said to Rush, thou lewd fellow, what hast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ?
ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

And then they began to muse: why the Priour thus displaied in a begginge, and his maisters so much in riches? Why is it that the good man of the house and the Priour so content ? Then they mused what would be betweene the wedded husband and wife, if the good man of the house or his wife should say unto the Priour, what hast thou done to us ? Why hast thou made us so glad, with thy riches and thy begging ? And the Priour should answer, for the love that I have unto you, I have done no such thing. ocr.region: 274 A PLEASANT HISTORIE had been there should have seene good buffets given on both parties. And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of Hght therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, be tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portaU of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portad into the Quier among aU the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to faU among your selves ? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good

prediction.sentence: And the King being out of the church, he saw the deske over the portall of the Quier, and he said to the Friers, what shall we do with these, where are they wounded and maimed for Gods sake, where is a man of us so valiant, that he shall bring them out of the Quier, to make amends for this wrong. They answered them, O King, if we could find any man that would doe soo, we would gladly doe it, but we have no man to be had now that is able to doe any good to these Friers. Then the King said, there is a man in the Quier, that we may well doe with, who can be had, he is a man of strength, who dare to fight with any, and there is not any of our Friers that can resist him, we will bring him away, and so we did, and brought him away unto the King, who was exceeding glad, for he was in a passion, and was ready to be a Christian. So when the King came out of the Quier, they took him, and carried him to his place in the field, and there he put on his garments of a soldier, and hee would have fought against the Friers, but they told him, they had done them a great wrong, and they would have him not to fight with them, but be his friend, and the King gave them his word,

And now my worthy Lord, I pray thee tell me, that if there had bene a Jew in this Quier, and you had seene him, and he had had his truncheon in his hand, and had laid thereon your owne body, howe would you have acted ? Thou wouldest have put him in prison, or cast him out of thy house for the Jewes cause. I say this to thee, my Lord, as it were to show the great difference in us, that while we be Friers, and have our brethren for our foes, we are no more than a packe of coy dogs, yet for to looke after their goods, our souls may perish in a day, and not a man care for his brethren, or he is not a Frier. But when we be Christians, and have them as brethren in God, we are nowe no coy dogs, but a man who would perish for his brethren, and no man be so bold to cast them out of his house, or to imprison them, neither for to take away their goods.
Now my Lord, what meanes this, if they be not such brethren ? Another time it fortuned that the Priour had a journey to ride into the country about a Httle businesse that hee had there to doe, and anon he caUed Rush his servant unto him and said, Rush goe thy way into the court, and take with thee a dish fuU ofgreace. and greace weU the wheeles and axeltrees of the waggon, and make aU things ready against to-morrow in the morning, for I must ride forth to-morrow betimes, then Rush departed from his maister, and went about bis businesse, and insteed of greace, hee tooke a great vesseU full of tarre, and anointed the w-aggon all over with it, both within and without, and especiaUy in the place where the Priour should sit and when he had done, he returned to his maister's chamber, then the Priour demanded of Rush, if he had done as he commanded him yea sir said Rush, ye may ride when please you, aud so they weut to their beds. ANOTHER time it fortuned that the Priour had a journey to ride into the country about a little businesse that hee had there to doe, and anon he called Rush his servant unto him and said, Rush goe thy way into the court, and take with thee a dish full of greace, and greace well the wheeles and axeltrees of the waggon, and make all things ready against to-morrow in the morning, for I must ride forth to-morrow betimes, then Rush departed from his maister, and went about his businesse, and insteed of greace, hee tooke a great vessell full of tarre, and anointed the waggon all over with it, both within and without, and especially in the place where the Priour should sit and when he had done, he returned to his maister's chamber, then the Priour demanded of Rush, if he had done as he commanded him yea sir said Rush, ye may ride when please you, and so they went to their beds. Then on the morrow after, the Priour and Rush his servant with his other company, rose up very early in the morning for to accomplish their journey, and forth they went unto their waggon, and when the Priour was entred therein, hee perceived himselfe all to betrayed and smeyred, and all his clothes were filed therewith and

And when they were gone forth of the Priours house, they went into a deserted country for to haue rest of their journey
prediction.region: grece, and so were the axeltrees, and the wheeles, and the whole of the vehicUle, and all the commodities, and goods that were in the wagon. Now, as soon as the Priour perceived this, hee fell to the ground aweeping bitterly, and his tears ran downe as it were a fountain of dew, and Rush came vnto him and sawe what hap had beene, and cried with all his might, Why dost thou weep, Priour? said hee, for I shall die for this sin that I have committed, and have in this manner done my businesse. Why, Rush said hee, this is but the begining of all that shall be done in my place. I saw the Priour that morning all in his sinne, and that he had committed the same in the most heinous manner. Now, the next morning hee sent for another man whom hee appointed him, and hee commanded him to take the Priour out of the wagon into the forest, and to cast him in a hole in the ground, and to put vpon him a great coatie of grease, and to close the hole with a great stone, and after hee had done his businesse, he returned into the town, and told all his company of what he had done, and they were sore gryed that he had cast the Priour so in the ground, and that he had inuade the holy things of the church, but the Priour made answer, that it was of good accord with God to cast him in the ground, for he had done all things which God in his holy law commanded him. And so he returned into his house, and told all his company of his matter, and as soon as it was knowne to the Bishop, he sent vnto him for the Priour, and hee was brought unto him

ocr.sentence: their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly.
ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 273 filling their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Frier Rush had delivered aH his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, either one time or other. So it fortuned afterward, as it is a common cus-tome among religious people at an high feast, to keepe solemne service, and every man to be at Mattens at midnight, and so upon a good night, all the whole Covent assembled together in the Quier, and were ready to begin Mattens, they taried for nothing but for the comming of the Priour. Then anon the Priour came into the Quier, and sate him downe in his place, and as he looked about him, he espied that the Subpriour was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge of the olde anger that was fallen betweene them two, and he thought in his minde that he could never be revenged in a better time, and sodainly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subpriour, and with his fist he gave him a good buffet, and the Subpriour which was moved with the stroke, started unto the Priour and gave him another buffet, and with that they went freshly together by the eares, and when the other Friers saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their Truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

ocr.sentence: who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and killed it, so were they both released from their danger.
ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 243 George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and kdled it, so were they both released from their danger. They being not contented with this tryall of their skill, went further in their coniurations, and raised up two spirits, each of them one. Bungye charged his spirit for to assist him with the greatest power hee had, that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devdl told him he would, if that he from his left arme would give him but three drops of blood but if that he did deny him that, then should Vandermast have power over him to doe what he would the Hke told Vandermasts Devill to him to this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking for to overcome each other but the Devill overthrew them both. They having given the Devill this bloud, as is before spoken of, they both fell againe to their coniurations first, Bungye did rayse Achilles with bis Greekes, who marched about Vandermast and threatned him. And for all that his father and mother were of an other religion, yet he had great favour with them all. And when he began to get to age, and saw that his young master was come to perfection, he began to love him for his devotion, and he did so that he was well liked of his father and mother also, that he would not marry them, but that he loved their son, and would keep him all his life. And his young master, who was named Rush, he made a great will unto his death to have that his young master was to have his body and his goods also to serve for ever in the house of God. And when his young master died, he made his will according as he had foretold. And as his young master was the great man of the house, and his father and mother hewed great pains and labours, to keepe him still in his holy living, he was so pious, that he feared God all the time, and was always willing to serve and to please God.
